>>If you can copy applications, you ca infect them.
>Do you mean, a virus copies the application onto another place for
>infecting them?

I actually meant that the virus would infect applications eitehr when
the user copied the application or just modified the on disk copies.

>Of course if you have a virus in the memory and unlock some sectors for
>changing them then the virus can infect something.

Yes.  If you lock certain sectors, at a certain moment you're going to
have to unlock them.  BTW, is this another PC-type controller thingy
that doesn't work for SCSI disks?

>It is transparent to the user except the process of locking/unlocking
>sectors.

Which is why it won't do much good.  Users tend to disable stuff that
gets in their way.

